    "\n",
    "## Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "Customer satisfaction is an important outcome for firms because it is often connected to loyalty, repeat purchase, positive word of mouth, and long-term customer value. However, knowing that customers are satisfied or dissatisfied is not enough. Managers also need to understand *which perceptions are most strongly associated with satisfaction*.\n",
    "\n",
    "This analysis uses a customer satisfaction survey dataset to identify the most important drivers of satisfaction. The survey includes several perception measures, such as whether the brand is trusted, whether the product is easy to use, whether it has appealing rewards, and whether it provides strong customer service.\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal of this analysis is to replicate the type of key driver table shown in the course slides. Specifically, I calculate several different measures of variable importance:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Pearson correlations\n",
    "- Standardized multiple regression coefficients\n",
    "- Drop-one usefulness\n",
    "- LMG / Shapley values for a linear regression\n",
    "- Johnson's relative weights\n",
    "- Mean decrease in Gini coefficient from a random forest\n",
    "\n",
    "Polychoric correlations are omitted, as allowed by the assignment instructions.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Research question\n",
    "\n",
    "The main research question is:\n",
    "\n",
    "> Which customer perceptions are the most important drivers of overall customer satisfaction?\n",
    "\n",
    "To answer this question, I compare multiple importance metrics rather than relying on only one method. This is useful because different methods capture different aspects of the relationship between perception variables and satisfaction."
   ]
  },
