    "The analysis uses complete cases, meaning that rows with missing values in the outcome or driver variables are removed. This keeps the comparison across methods consistent because each method uses the same set of observations.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 3. Method overview\n",
    "\n",
    "A key driver analysis tries to determine which explanatory variables matter most for an outcome. In this case, the outcome is satisfaction.\n",
    "\n",
    "No single method is perfect. For example, Pearson correlations are simple and easy to understand, but they do not account for overlap among predictors. Regression coefficients account for other variables, but they can be unstable when predictors are correlated. Shapley values and Johnson's relative weights are useful because they decompose model explanatory power across predictors.\n",
    "\n",
    "For this reason, I use several methods and compare whether the same variables appear important across methods."
   ]
  },
