    "The final analysis includes nine possible drivers of satisfaction. These nine drivers are compared across all importance methods.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 5. Pearson correlations\n",
    "\n",
    "Pearson correlations measure the simple bivariate relationship between each perception variable and satisfaction.\n",
    "\n",
    "A high Pearson correlation means that customers who rate that perception higher also tend to report higher satisfaction. However, Pearson correlations do not control for the other perception variables. Therefore, they are useful as an initial measure but should not be interpreted as the only evidence of importance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "pearson-correlations",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#| label: pearson-correlations\n",
    "\n",
    "pearson_raw = np.array([\n",
    "    np.corrcoef(X_z[:, j], y_z)[0, 1]\n",
    "    for j in range(n_drivers)\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "pearson_pct = normalize_to_100(\n",
    "    pearson_raw,\n",
    "    use_absolute=True\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e9a23809",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Standardized multiple regression coefficients\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, I estimate a multiple linear regression model predicting satisfaction from all nine perception variables.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because the variables are standardized, the regression coefficients can be compared directly. A larger standardized coefficient means that a variable has a stronger relationship with satisfaction after controlling for the other variables in the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "standardized-regression",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/markdown": [
       "The full linear regression model has an R-squared of **0.109**."
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "<IPython.core.display.Markdown object>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#| label: standardized-regression\n",
    "#| echo: true\n",
    "#| code-fold: false\n",
    "\n",
    "standardized_lm = LinearRegression()\n",
    "standardized_lm.fit(X_z, y_z)\n",
    "\n",
    "standardized_betas_raw = standardized_lm.coef_\n",
    "\n",
    "standardized_betas_pct = normalize_to_100(\n",
    "    standardized_betas_raw,\n",
    "    use_absolute=True\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "full_model_r2 = standardized_lm.score(X_z, y_z)\n",
    "\n",
    "display(Markdown(f\"The full linear regression model has an R-squared of **{full_model_r2:.3f}**.\"))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e5fd6b0e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The R-squared value shows the proportion of variation in satisfaction explained by the full set of perception variables. A higher R-squared means the perception variables collectively explain more of the differences in customer satisfaction.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7. Drop-one usefulness\n",
    "\n",
    "Drop-one usefulness measures how much model performance decreases when a variable is removed from the full regression model.\n",
    "\n",
    "The logic is simple: if removing a variable causes a large drop in R-squared, then that variable is useful for explaining satisfaction. If removing a variable barely changes R-squared, then that variable contributes little unique explanatory power beyond the other variables."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "drop-one-usefulness",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#| label: drop-one-usefulness\n",
    "#| echo: true\n",
    "#| code-fold: false\n",
    "\n",
    "all_features = list(range(n_drivers))\n",
    "\n",
    "drop_one_raw = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for j in range(n_drivers):\n",
    "    features_without_j = [\n",
    "        idx for idx in all_features\n",
    "        if idx != j\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "\n",
    "    r2_without_j = r2_score_for_features(\n",
    "        X_z,\n",
    "        y_z,\n",
    "        features_without_j\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    usefulness_j = full_model_r2 - r2_without_j\n",
    "    drop_one_raw.append(usefulness_j)\n",
    "\n",
    "drop_one_raw = np.array(drop_one_raw)\n",
    "\n",
    "drop_one_pct = normalize_to_100(\n",
    "    drop_one_raw,\n",
    "    use_absolute=False\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3b9709bd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Drop-one usefulness is especially helpful because it focuses on the unique contribution of each variable when the full set of variables is already included in the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 8. LMG / Shapley values\n",
    "\n",
    "LMG / Shapley values provide a more comprehensive way to measure variable importance in a linear regression.\n",
    "\n",
    "The idea is to calculate how much each variable improves R-squared across all possible orders in which variables could be added to the model. This helps address the problem that correlated predictors can share explanatory power. Instead of assigning all shared explanatory power to whichever variable enters first, Shapley values fairly average the marginal contribution across all possible orderings."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "shapley-values",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
