       "The Shapley values sum to **0.109**, which equals the model R-squared."
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "<IPython.core.display.Markdown object>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#| label: shapley-values\n",
    "#| echo: true\n",
    "#| code-fold: false\n",
    "\n",
    "shapley_raw = exact_shapley_r2_values(X_z, y_z)\n",
    "\n",
    "shapley_pct = normalize_to_100(\n",
    "    shapley_raw,\n",
    "    use_absolute=False\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "display(Markdown(f\"The Shapley values sum to **{shapley_raw.sum():.3f}**, which equals the model R-squared.\"))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0ef01b3f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this analysis, Shapley values are calculated exactly using R-squared as the fit metric. This directly follows the optional challenge described in the assignment.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 9. Johnson's relative weights\n",
    "\n",
    "Johnson's relative weights are another method for decomposing R-squared among predictors.\n",
    "\n",
    "This method is useful when predictors are correlated. Instead of relying only on standardized regression coefficients, Johnson's relative weights transform the correlated predictors into orthogonal components and then allocate explained variance back to the original predictors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "johnson-relative-weights",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
