   "source": [
    "The Shapley and Johnson methods are especially important for interpretation because both methods decompose the explanatory power of the regression model. If the same perceptions are highly ranked by both methods, then those perceptions are likely to be meaningful drivers of satisfaction.\n",
    "\n",
    "The random forest results provide an additional predictive perspective. If a perception is also important in the random forest model, that suggests the variable is useful not only in a linear regression framework but also in a more flexible machine-learning model.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 13. Managerial implications\n",
    "\n",
    "From a managerial perspective, the most important variables in the key driver table should receive the greatest attention. These are the perceptions most strongly connected to customer satisfaction.\n",
    "\n",
    "For example, if trust, customer service, or perceived impact appear near the top across multiple methods, then managers should prioritize actions that improve those perceptions. This could include strengthening brand credibility, improving customer support quality, clarifying product benefits, or communicating the product's value more effectively.\n",
    "\n",
    "The key point is that customer satisfaction should not be improved through guesswork. A key driver analysis helps identify which parts of the customer experience are most closely associated with satisfaction, allowing managers to focus resources on the areas that are most likely to matter.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 14. Limitations\n",
    "\n",
    "This analysis has several limitations.\n",
    "\n",
    "First, the results are based on survey data, so the relationships should be interpreted as associations rather than definitive causal effects. A variable may be strongly related to satisfaction, but this does not automatically prove that changing that perception would cause satisfaction to increase.\n",
    "\n",
    "Second, several perception variables may be correlated with each other. This makes variable importance more difficult to measure. For that reason, this analysis uses Shapley values and Johnson's relative weights in addition to simple correlations and regression coefficients.\n",
